{"title_page": "Carlos Sosa (musician)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Carlos Sosa\n| image            = Carlos Sosa Grooveline Saxophone.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Carlos Sosa performing October 2010.\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date|1974|04|06}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = [[San Antonio, Texas]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|\n* [[funk]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* [[Latin music|latin]]}}\n| occupation       = {{Flatlist|\n* Musician\n* [[Record producer|Producer]]\n* Arranger\n* [[Composer]]\n* [[Music director#Pop music|Music Director]]\n* [[Audio engineer|Recording Engineer]]\n* [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Audio Mixing]]}}\n| instrument       = [[Tenor saxophone|Tenor Saxophone]]<br>[[Baritone saxophone|Baritone Saxophone]]<br>[[Flute]]\n| years_active     = 1996\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{Flatlist|\n* '''[[Grooveline Horns]]'''\n* [[Maroon 5]]\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n* [[Jason Mraz]]\n* [[Zac Brown Band]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Sosa''' is an American musician, [[Record producer|producer]], [[composer]], [[Music director#Pop music|music director]], and arranger. Heavily influenced by the R&B and funk sounds of the 1970s, Sosa founded '''[[Grooveline Horns]]''' in 1996, and is best known for touring and recording with [[Maroon 5]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Jason Mraz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2010-01-15/938273/|title=Off the Record}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2010-01-22/940883/|title=Off the Record}}</ref> and [[Zac Brown Band]].\n\n==Early influences and career==\nSosa started playing saxophone around the age of 10. When he was 15, he joined a funk band and started playing clubs in Texas. Heavily influenced by [[Earth, Wind & Fire]], [[James Brown]] and [[Parliament-Funkadelic]], he knew his musical preferences leaned heavily towards funk, R&B, soul and pop music.\n\nHe attended [[Texas State University]], getting a degree in [[Audio engineer|Audio Engineering]]. While in college, he formed '''Grooveline Horns''' and they played with various cover bands on [[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|6th Street]], honing their versatility.  Within a short time, they began playing with Austin musician [[Bob Schneider]]. This led to bigger acts using the group including Don Henley, Suicidal Tendencies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weeklywire.com/ww/07-08-97/austin_music_liveshots.html|title=Music: Live Shots (Austin Chronicle . 07\u201308\u201397)|first=wil gerken, nathan hendler, doug floyd, amy burnham, zak|last=woodruff|website=weeklywire.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://diversearts.org/content/v3n6-august-1997|title=V3N6: August 1997 \u2013 DiverseArts Culture Works|website=diversearts.org}}</ref> and Kelly Clarkson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://badgerherald.com/blogs/thebeatgoeson/2009/05/03/talking-with-carlos/|title=Talking with Carlos Sosa, saxophonist for Jason Mraz}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2009\n| [[We Sing. We Dance. We Steal Things.]], [[Jason Mraz]]\n| [[2009 Teen Choice Awards]]\n| {{Won}} \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2005\n| Best Groupera Album, La Mafia\n| Latin Grammy Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/grooveline-horns/grooveline-show-are-you-ready/123290027007/|title=Grooveline Show! Are you ready?|website=facebook.com}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2018}}</ref>\n| {{Won}} \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2004\n| Spanish Album of the Year, [[Con Poder (Salvador album)|Con Poder]], [[Salvador (band)|Salvador]]<ref>[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=2004 GMA Dove Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022920/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=2004 |date=October 20, 2006 }}</ref>\n| [[35th GMA Dove Awards]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1997\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns, The Scabs\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:1997/category:best-austin-musicians/512747/|title=Grooveline Horns (The Scabs) \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 1997 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1998\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:1998/category:best-austin-musicians/513249/|title=Grooveline Horns \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 1998 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1999\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:1999/category:best-austin-musicians/513659/|title=Grooveline Horns \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 1999 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2000\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns, The Scabs\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:2000/category:best-austin-musicians/516407/|title=Grooveline Horns, the Scabs \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 2000 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2001\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:2001/category:best-austin-musicians/145467/|title=Grooveline Horns \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 2001 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2003\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:2003/category:best-austin-musicians/202722/|title=Grooveline Horns \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 2003 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2006\n| Best Horns: Grooveline Horns\n| Austin Music Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/austin-music-awards/year:2006/category:best-austin-musicians/455956/|title=Grooveline Horns \u2013 Best Horns \u2013 Austin Music Awards \u2013 2006 \u2013 Best Austin Musicians \u2013 The Austin Chronicle|website=austinchronicle.com}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n{{end table}}\n\n== Discography ==\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/carlos-sosa-mn0000177692/credits|title=Carlos Sosa \u2013 Credits|publisher=AllMusic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/690328-Carlos-Sosa-2|title=Carlos Sosa (2)|publisher=discogs}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n! Artist\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Credits\n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Finally It's Christmas]]\n| [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]]\n| Engineer, Horn Arrangements, Saxophone\n|-\n|2017\n|Sir Rosevelt\n|[[Sir Rosevelt]]\n|Saxophone, arranger\n|-\n|-\n| 2017\n| Jesse & Joy\n| [[Jesse & Joy]]\n| Saxophone\n|-\n| 2017\n| Lay It on Down\n| [[Kenny Wayne Shepherd|Kenny Wayne Shepherd Band / Kenny Wayne Shepherd]]\n| Saxophone\n|-\n| 2017\n| Until My Voice Goes Out\n| [[Josh Abbott Band]]\n| Producer, engineer, Saxophone, Horn Arrangements\n|-\n| 2016\n| Spark\n| [[Drake White]]\n| Saxophone\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Big Trouble (Outasight album)|Big Trouble]]\n| [[Outasight