2015\n| Ven a Cristo\n| Alex Perez\n| Composer\n|-\n| 2012\n| Wax Motif & Neoteric Present Strictly Rhythms, Vol. 9\n| Various Artists\n| Composer\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Single\n! Artist\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Credits\n|-\n| 2015\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gEbcEYbxmqQ The Wild Life]\n| [[Outasight]]\n| Composer\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n<!-- [[File:Carlos Sosa Jason Mraz.jpg|thumb|left|Carlos Sosa performing with Jason Mraz]] -->\n\n==Music community and advocacy==\n[[File:Carlos Sosa Grooveline Horns Musician Rights.jpg|thumb|Carlos Sosa discussing musician rights.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ceeWmhCXUzs|title=Carlos Sosa of Grooveline Horns on Musician's rights|last=amfmstudios|date=May 24, 2010|via=YouTube}}</ref>]]\n\nCarlos is an active member of the [[The Recording Academy#Chapters|Texas Chapter]] Board of Governors for the [[The Recording Academy|Recording Academy]] (also known as the GRAMMYs), having held office as both President and Vice President.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/austin-creative-class-its-own|title=Austin Is in a Creative Class of Its Own|date=March 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.com/license/117061507|title=Texas Chapter President Carlos Sosa speaks to attendees at the...}}</ref>\n\nHe is on the board of directors for the SIMS Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://simsfoundation.org/our-story/board-of-directors/|title=Board of Directors SIMS Foundation|website=simsfoundation.org}}</ref> and has advocated with local politicians regarding the epidemic of opioid abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://communityimpact.com/austin/central-austin/healthcare/2018/06/27/austin-music-community-looks-for-help-in-struggle-to-end-opioid-abuse/|title=Austin music community looks for help in struggle to end opioid abuse \u2013 Community Impact Newspaper|date=June 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSosa is also an Advisory Board Member<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackfret.org/carlos-sosa/|title=Carlos Sosa \u2013 Black Fret Advisory Board Member \u2013 Producer|website=blackfret.org}}</ref> of Black Fret, a non-profit organization that provides grants and mentorship to musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blackfret.org/about-black-fret/#what-we-do|title=About Black Fret \u2013 A Patrons of Local Music Organization|website=blackfret.org}}</ref>\n\nHe has advocated for passing laws for royalty payments for musicians in the US, providing parity with the rest of the world.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAfter the 2017 [[2017 Las Vegas shooting|Las Vegas shooting]] while playing with Josh Abbott band,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/band-member-describes-vegas-massacre-chaos-1202578727/|title=A Band Member Describes Backstage Vegas Chaos: \u2018Just Hearing the Screaming Was Nightmarish\u2019|first=Chris|last=Willman|date=October 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Witnesses-Describe-Gunman-Shooting-Las-Vegas-449035873.html|title=Las Vegas Shooting Witnesses Describe the Terrifying Moments}}</ref> he urged fans to continue going to shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/austin-musician-performing-at-vegas-concert-hopes-people-keep-coming-to-shows_20180312074801877/1031431564|title=Austin musician at Vegas shooting urges fans to continue coming to shows|first=Alicia|last=Inns|date=October 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/groovelinesosa Facebook]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/groovelinesosa/ Instagram]\n* [https://twitter.com/groovelinesosa Twitter]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlos Sosa}}\n[[Category:American horn players]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Brass musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Carlos Sosa\n| image            = Carlos Sosa Grooveline Saxophone.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Carlos Sosa performing October 2010.\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date|1974|04|06}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place      = [[San Antonio, Texas]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|\n* [[funk]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* [[Latin music|latin]]}}\n| occupation       = {{Flatlist|\n* Musician\n* [[Record producer|Producer]]\n* Arranger\n* [[Composer]]\n* [[Music director#Pop music|Music Director]]\n* [[Audio engineer|Recording Engineer]]\n* [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|Audio Mixing]]}}\n| instrument       = [[Tenor saxophone|Tenor Saxophone]]<br>[[Baritone saxophone|Baritone Saxophone]]<br>[[Flute]]\n| years_active     = 1996\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = {{Flatlist|\n* '''[[Grooveline Horns]]'''\n* [[Maroon 5]]\n* [[Kelly Clarkson]]\n* [[Jason Mraz]]\n* [[Zac Brown Band]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Sosa''' is an American musician, [[Record producer|producer]], [[composer]], [[Music director#Pop music|music director]], and arranger. Heavily influenced by the R&B and funk sounds of the 1970s, Sosa founded '''[[Grooveline Horns]]''' in 1996, and is best known for touring and recording with [[Maroon 5]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Jason Mraz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2010-01-15/938273/|title=Off the Record}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2010-01-22/940883/|title=Off the Record}}</ref> and [[Zac Brown Band]].\n\n==Early influences and career==\nSosa started playing saxophone around the age of 10. When he was 15, he joined a funk band and started playing clubs in Texas. Heavily influenced by [[Earth, Wind & Fire]], [[James Brown]] and [[Parliament-Funkadelic]], he knew his musical preferences leaned heavily towards funk, R&B, soul and pop music.\n\nHe attended [[Texas State University]], getting a degree in [[Audio engineer|Audio Engineering]]. While in college, he formed '''Grooveline Horns''' and they played with various cover bands on [[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|6th Street]], honing their versatility.  Within a short time, they began playing with Austin musician [[Bob Schneider]]. This led to bigger acts using the group including Don Henley, Suicidal Tendencies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weeklywire.com/ww/07-08-97/austin_music_liveshots.html|title=Music: Live Shots (Austin Chronicle . 07\u201308\u201397)|first=wil gerken, nathan hendler, doug floyd, amy burnham, zak|last=woodruff|website=weeklywire.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://diversearts.org/content/v3n6-august-1997|title=V3N6: August 1997 \u2013 DiverseArts Culture Works|website=diversearts.org}}</ref> and Kelly Clarkson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://badgerherald.com/blogs/thebeatgoeson/2009/05/03/talking-with-carlos/|title=Talking with Carlos Sosa, saxophonist for Jason Mraz}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2009\n| [[We Sing. We Dance. We Steal Things.]], [[Jason Mraz]]\n| [[2009 Teen Choice Awards]]\n| {{Won}} \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2005\n| Best Groupera Album, La Mafia\n| Latin Grammy Awards<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/grooveline-horns/grooveline-show-are-you-ready/123290027007/|title=Grooveline Show! Are you ready?|website=facebook.com}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2018}}</ref>\n| {{Won}} \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2004\n| Spanish Album of the Year, [[Con Poder (Salvador album)|Con Poder]], [[Salvador (band)|Salvador]]<ref>[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=2004 GMA Dove Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022920/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=2004 |date=October 20, 2006 }}</ref>\n| [[35th GMA Dove Awards]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1997