{"title_page": "Michael Barr (software engineer)", "text_new": "{{notability|bio|date=March 2011}}\n'''Michael Barr''' is a [[software engineer]] specializing in software design for medical devices and other [[embedded system]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Struggle Continues to Plug Embedded Programming Gap |url=http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4372250/Struggle-continues-to-plug-embedded-programming-gap |first=George |last=Leopold |work=EE Times |date=2012-05-03 |accessdate=2012-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Embedded Systems Design Magazine Editorial Contacts - Michael Barr |url=http://www.embedded.com/staff/michael.htm |work=Embedded |accessdate=2007-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061110101319/http://www.embedded.com/staff/michael.htm |archivedate=November 10, 2006 }}</ref> He is a past editor-in-chief of Embedded Systems Design magazine<ref>{{cite web|work=O'Reilly Media, Inc.|title=Michael Barr - Biography|accessdate=2007-04-21|url=http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/au/670}}</ref> and author of three books and more than seventy articles about embedded software.<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Scholar|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&q=michael+barr+embedded+-epstein+-tumor&btnG=&as_sdt=1%2C21|accessdate=2013-06-13}}</ref>\n\nBarr has often worked as an expert witness, including testifying in the [[Toyota]] [[Sudden Unintended Acceleration]] litigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Toyota Attacks Alleged Evidence of Accelerator Software Bug|accessdate=2013-09-20|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202616130170}}</ref>  In October 2013, after reviewing Toyota's source code as part of a team of seven engineers, he testified in a jury trial in Oklahoma that led to a \"guilty by software defects\" finding against Toyota.  There are several technical articles that discuss the various [[electronic throttle control]] defects he testified were linked to unintended acceleration that caused deaths in [[Toyota Camry]] vehicles.\n<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.edn.com/design/automotive/4423428/Toyota-s-killer-firmware--Bad-design-and-its-consequences |title=Toyota's killer firmware: Bad design and its consequences |first=Michael |last=Dunn |work=EDN |date=2013-10-28 |accessdate=2013-11-25}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1319936 |title=Toyota Trial: Transcript Reveals 'Task X' Clues |first=Junko |last=Yoshida |work=EE Times |date=2013-10-29 |accessdate=2013-11-25}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1319903 |title=Toyota Case: Single Bit Flip That Killed |first=Junko |last=Yoshida |work=EE Times |date=2013-10-25 |accessdate=2013-11-25}}</ref>\n\nEarlier in his career, Barr testified as an expert witness in the [[DirecTV]] anti-piracy [[DirecTV#Access card history|end user litigation, which involved over 25,000 end users]].<ref name=CV/>  He has also worked as a testifying expert witness in other high-profile litigation involving software, such as SmartPhone Technologies vs [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and in a copyright dispute about [[Electronic Arts|EA]]'s early [[Madden NFL|Madden Football]] video game source code.<ref>{{cite web|title=EA Can't Sink 'Madden' Royalties Suit in Jury Trial|accessdate=2013-06-22|url=http://www.law360.com/articles/452353/jury-says-madden-programmer-s-royalties-suit-is-timely}}</ref>\n\nBarr began his career working as an embedded programmer at [[Hughes Network Systems]], where he wrote software for products including the first-generation Hughes-branded [[DirecTV]] receiver, which sold in the millions of units.  He subsequently wrote embedded software at TSI TelSys, PropHead Development, and Netrino.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Barr Expert Witness Resume|url=http://netrino.com/images/cv-barr.pdf|accessdate=2011-09-14}}</ref>  His three books are ''Programming Embedded Systems in C with GNU Development Tools'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Programming Embedded Systems in C with GNU Development Tools|accessdate=2011-03-16|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0596009836}}</ref> ''Embedded Systems Dictionary''<ref>{{cite web|title=Embedded Systems Dictionary|accessdate=2011-03-16|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1578201209}}</ref> (co-authored by Jack Ganssle), and \"Embedded C Coding Standard\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Embedded C Coding Standard|accessdate=2011-03-16|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1442164824}}</ref>\n\nBarr studied electrical engineering at the [[University of Maryland]] in College Park, from which he earned a Bachelor of Science degree in 1994 and a Master of Science degree in 1997.<ref name=CV>{{cite web|title=Curriculum Vitae of Michael Barr|accessdate=2012-06-03|url=http://www.netrino.com/images/cv-barr.pdf}}</ref>  From 2000\u20132002, he taught ENEE 447 Operating Systems Theory as an adjunct professor in the same Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering.<ref name=CV/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.embeddedgurus.com/barr-code Barr Code] blog\n* [http://www.barrgroup.com Barr Group] website\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070609183819/http://www.embedded.com/mag.htm Embedded Systems Design] magazine (formerly Embedded Systems Programming)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barr, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n\n\n{{Compu-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|bio|date=March 2011}}\n'''Michael Barr''' is a [[software engineer]] specializing in software design for medical devices and other [[embedded system]]s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Struggle Continues to Plug Embedded Programming Gap |url=http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4372250/Struggle-continues-to-plug-embedded-programming-gap |first=George |last=Leopold |work=EE Times |date=2012-05-03 |accessdate=2012-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Embedded Systems Design Magazine Editorial Contacts - Michael Barr |url=http:/