lej]]|NED}} || 5.4 || 7.800 ||  || '''13.200'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150929172051/https://utrecht2013.com/sportform/xzgy/files/7e5f93f0_2013-07-16=Utrecht-EYOF-Results.pdf Results]\n\n{{Events at the 2013 European Youth Summer Olympic Festival}}\n\n[[Category:2013 in gymnastics|European Youth Summer Olympic Festival]]\n[[Category:2013 European Youth Summer Olympic Festival]]\n[[Category:Gymnastics at the European Youth Summer Olympic Festival|2013]]\n[[Category:International gymnastics competitions hosted by the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Matterington", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gymnastics_at_the_2013_European_Youth_Summer_Olympic_Festival"}
{"title_page": "Riversimple Urban Car", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Riversimple Urban Car.jpg|thumb|CAD drawing of the Riversimple Urban Car]]\n\nThe '''Riversimple Urban Car''' is a conceptual [[Open-source model|open source]] [[hydrogen]] [[fuel cell vehicle]] that was proposed by [[Hugo Spowers]]' company, [[Riversimple]], in 2009. Their latest model, the [[Riversimple|Rasa]], was unveiled on 17 February 2016.\n\nA working prototype vehicle was unveiled at the [[Somerset House]] in London on 16 June 2009, and {{asof|2009|lc=y}}, with production initially planned to begin by 2013.<ref name=\"dvice\">{{cite web|last=Dugdale |first=Addy |url=http://dvice.com/archives/2009/06/riversimple-urb.php |title=dvice.com |publisher=dvice.com |date=2009-06-17 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> The plan has been subsequently superseded with the intention to develop a production vehicle of a similar format but with a new design in 2018\u201319.\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe Riversimple Urban Car was designed and developed in the [[United Kingdom]] by teams at [[Cranfield University|Cranfield]] and [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] Universities. It was backed by Sebastian Piech, the great-grandson of [[Ferdinand Porsche]].<ref name=\"Autocar article\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/AllCars/240683/ |title=Autocar article |publisher=Autocar article |date=2009-06-09 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Urban Car is a two-passenger vehicle about the size of a [[Smart (marque)|Smart]]. It weighs {{convert|772|lb|kg}}, and the prototype was constructed of a [[Carbon fiber]] [[composite material]] body.<ref name=\"riversimple1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?mode=menu&type=7&key=136c7243-2378-407e-96cf-750d15de37a8 |title=Riversimple website |publisher=Riversimple.com |accessdate=2010-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317105213/http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?type=7&mode=menu&key=136c7243-2378-407e-96cf-750d15de37a8 |archivedate=17 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The car can reach speeds of {{Convert|50|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} and travel for {{convert|240|mi|km}} on {{convert|2.2|lb|kg}} of [[hydrogen]] before refueling.<ref name=eg20100208>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/06/16/hydrogen-powered-riversimple-urban-car-unveiled-makes-your-hybr/ |title=engadget.com |publisher=engadget.com |date= |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> 2010 calculations showed it could achieve the equivalent of up to 300 [[Miles per gallon|mpg]] in hydrogen,<ref name=\"Autocar article\"/> and a [[life cycle assessment]] [[Greenhouse gas|carbon emissions]] of less than 30g CO<sub>2</sub>/km.<ref name=\"Hyrban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.40fires.org/Wiki.jsp?page=The%20Hyrban |title=Hyrban project |publisher=40fires.org |date= |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>{{update after|2013|8|12}}\n\n== Operation ==\n\nThe Urban Car is powered by a [[fuel cell]] from [[Horizon Fuel Cell Technologies]]<ref>{{cite web \n|url=http://www.horizonfuelcell.com/#!autopak-/cpor \n|title=AUTOPAK Automotive fuel cell System |website=Horizon Fuel Cell Technologies |accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref> that converts hydrogen into electricity. This power supply functions like a [[battery (electricity)|battery]], uses no moving parts, and emits only pure water. There are two novel principles involved with this project: decoupling of acceleration from cruising, and mass decompounding.\n\n''[[Decoupling (electronics)|Decoupling]] acceleration and cruise'' means that the fuel cell will only need to be large enough to supply the power needed for maintaining a constant speed, which is about 20% of the power needed for acceleration. Most of the car's braking is done by [[electric motor]]s on each wheel. These motors capture the energy of the car in motion, and store it as electricity in a bank of [[electric double-layer capacitor]]s (ultra-capacitors). This electricity is used to provide 75% of the power used in acceleration. Because of this, the Urban Car can be powered by a 6&nbsp;kW fuel cell, which is significantly smaller than the [[Honda FCX Clarity]]'s 100&nbsp;kW fuel cell. This requires less hydrogen to be stored on board, and results in an overall lighter vehicle.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" />\n\n''Mass decompounding'' involves designing the car as a complete system, as opposed to redesigning a car originally conceived as being powered by an [[internal combustion engine]] into a fuel cell vehicle. The combination of a small fuel cell, along with elimination of the unnecessary [[Transmission (mechanics)|gearbox]], [[drive shaft]]s, power-assist systems, and associated components, results in a very lightweight vehicle.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" />\n\n== Retail and licensing ==\n\n{{asof|2010|02}}, Riversimple planned to [[lease]] the cars over 15 years instead of selling them, with fueling included in the leasing cost. This was intended to increase the life of the vehicles, and reduce materials usage.<ref name=\"riversimple1\"/> The cost of the lease was expected to be about \u00a3200 (US$330) per month.<ref name=eg20100208/>\n\n{{asof|2010}}, the open source design for the Riversimple Urban Car was planned to be stored on the 40 Fires [[wiki]] site online. The wiki project is called ''The Hyrban''.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" /> \nAt that time, Riversimple planned to lease the design to any small manufacturer for free, modify it as desired, and build their own version of the vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/blog/60-second-science/post.cfm?id=an-open-source-hydrogen-car-with-a-2009-06-12&sc=DD_20090612 |title=An open-source hydrogen car with a Porsche pedigree |publisher= Scientific American |date=2009-06-12 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe CAD models for the Riversimple Hyrban technology demonstrator have been released{{when|date=August 2013}} under a Creative Commons license, attribution 3.0.\n<ref>\n[http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?key=4b94774e-90b8-412b-806c-96c728591765&mode= \"Why are you making your designs available under an Open Source license?\"]\n</ref><ref>\n[http://www.40fires.org/ \"The 40 Fires Foundation takes an open source approach to developing energy-efficient technology\"]\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Hydrogen economy]]\n* [[Morgan LIFEcar]]\n* [[List of fuel cell vehicles]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{official website|http://www.riversimple.com/|Riversimple corporate website}}\n* {{official website|http://www.40fires.org/|40 Fires Foundation open source design foundation}}\n* {{youtube|IHSOgw3Ecw0|Urban Car's debut}}\n\n[[Category:Hydrogen cars]]\n[[Category:Fuel cell vehicles]]\n[[Category:Concept cars]]\n[[Category:Open hardware vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Riversimple Urban Car.jpg|thumb|CAD drawing of the Riversimple Urban Car]]\n\nThe '''Riversimple Urban Car''' is a conceptual [[Open-source model|open source]] [[hydrogen]] [[fuel cell vehicle]] that was proposed by [[Hugo Spowers]]' company, [[Riversimple]], in 2009. Their latest model, the [[Riversimple|Rasa]], was unveiled on 17 February 2016.\n\nA working prototype vehicle was unveiled at the [[Somerset House]] in London on 16 June 2009, and {{asof|2009|lc=y}}, with production initially planned to begin by 2013.<ref name=\"dvice\">{{cite web|last=Dugdale |first=Addy |url=http://dvice.com/archives/2009/06/riversimple-urb.php |title=dvice.com |publisher=dvice.com |date=2009-06-17 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> The plan has been subsequently superseded with the intention to develop a production vehicle of a similar format but with a new design in 2018-19.\n\n== Design ==\n\nThe Riversimple Urban Car was designed and developed in the [[United Kingdom]] by teams at [[Cranfield University|Cranfield]] and [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] Universities. It was backed by Sebastian Piech, the great-grandson of [[Ferdinand Porsche]].<ref name=\"Autocar article\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/AllCars/240683/ |title=Autocar article |publisher=Autocar article |date=2009-06-09 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe Urban Car is a two passenger vehicle about the size of a [[Smart (marque)|Smart]]. It weighs {{convert|772|lb|kg}}, and the prototype was constructed of a [[Carbon fiber]] [[composite material]] body.<ref name=\"riversimple1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?mode=menu&type=7&key=136c7243-2378-407e-96cf-750d15de37a8 |title=Riversimple website |publisher=Riversimple.com |accessdate=2010-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317105213/http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?type=7&mode=menu&key=136c7243-2378-407e-96cf-750d15de37a8 |archivedate=17 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The car can reach speeds of {{Convert|50|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} and travel for {{convert|240|mi|km}} on {{convert|2.2|lb|kg}} of [[hydrogen]] before refueling.<ref name=eg20100208>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/06/16/hydrogen-powered-riversimple-urban-car-unveiled-makes-your-hybr/ |title=engadget.com |publisher=engadget.com |date= |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref> 2010 calculations showed it could achieve the equivalent of up to 300 [[Miles per gallon|mpg]] in hydrogen,<ref name=\"Autocar article\"/> and a [[life cycle assessment]] [[Greenhouse gas|carbon emissions]] of less than 30g CO<sub>2</sub>/km.<ref name=\"Hyrban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.40fires.org/Wiki.jsp?page=The%20Hyrban |title=Hyrban project |publisher=40fires.org |date= |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>{{update after|2013|8|12}}\n\n== Operation ==\n\nThe Urban Car is powered by a [[fuel cell]] from [[Horizon Fuel Cell Technologies]]<ref>{{cite web \n|url=http://www.horizonfuelcell.com/#!autopak-/cpor \n|title=AUTOPAK Automotive fuel cell System |website=Horizon Fuel Cell Technologies |accessdate=21 July 2013}}</ref> that converts hydrogen into electricity. This power supply functions like a [[battery (electricity)|battery]], uses no moving parts, and emits only pure water. There are two novel principles involved with this project: decoupling of acceleration from cruising, and mass decompounding.\n\n''[[Decoupling (electronics)|Decoupling]] acceleration and cruise'' means that the fuel cell will only need to be large enough to supply the power needed for maintaining a constant speed, which is about 20% of the power needed for acceleration. Most of the car's braking is done by [[electric motor]]s on each wheel. These motors capture the energy of the car in motion, and store it as electricity in a bank of [[electric double-layer capacitor]]s (ultra-capacitors). This electricity is used to provide 75% of the power used in acceleration. Because of this, the Urban Car can be powered by a 6&nbsp;kW fuel cell, which is significantly smaller than the [[Honda FCX Clarity]]'s 100&nbsp;kW fuel cell. This requires less hydrogen to be stored on board, and results in an overall lighter vehicle.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" />\n\n''Mass decompounding'' involves designing the car as a complete system, as opposed to redesigning a car originally conceived as being powered by an [[internal combustion engine]] into a fuel cell vehicle. The combination of a small fuel cell, along with elimination of the unnecessary [[Transmission (mechanics)|gearbox]], [[drive shaft]]s, power-assist systems, and associated components, results in a very lightweight vehicle.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" />\n\n== Retail and licensing ==\n\n{{asof|2010|02}}, Riversimple planned to [[lease]] the cars over 15 years instead of selling them, with fueling included in the leasing cost. This was intended to increase the life of the vehicles, and reduce materials usage.<ref name=\"riversimple1\"/> The cost of the lease was expected to be about \u00a3200 (US$330) per month.<ref name=eg20100208/>\n\n{{asof|2010}}, the open source design for the Riversimple Urban Car was planned to be stored on the 40 Fires [[wiki]] site online. The wiki project is called ''The Hyrban''.<ref name=\"Hyrban\" /> \nAt that time, Riversimple planned to lease the design to any small manufacturer for free, modify it as desired, and build their own version of the vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/blog/60-second-science/post.cfm?id=an-open-source-hydrogen-car-with-a-2009-06-12&sc=DD_20090612 |title=An open-source hydrogen car with a Porsche pedigree |publisher= Scientific American |date=2009-06-12 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>\n\nThe CAD models for the Riversimple Hyrban technology demonstrator have been released{{when|date=August 2013}} under a Creative Commons license, attribution 3.0.\n<ref>\n[http://www.riversimple.com/Content.aspx?key=4b94774e-90b8-412b-806c-96c728591765&mode= \"Why are you making your designs available under an Open Source license?\"]\n</ref><ref>\n[http://www.40fires.org/ \"The 40 Fires Foundation takes an open source approach to developing energy-efficient technology\"]\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Hydrogen economy]]\n* [[Morgan LIFEcar]]\n* [[List of fuel cell vehicles]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{official website|http://www.riversimple.com/|Riversimple corporate website}}\n* {{official website|http://www.40fires.org/|40 Fires Foundation open source design foundation}}\n* {{youtube|IHSOgw3Ecw0|Urban Car's debut}}\n\n[[Category:Hydrogen cars]]\n[[Category:Fuel cell vehicles]]\n[[Category:Concept cars]]\n[[Category:Open hardware vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: two passenger \u2192 two-passenger, 2018-19 \u2192 2018\u201319", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riversimple_Urban_Car"}
{"title_page": "If the World Was Ending", "text_new": "{{short description|Song by JP Saxe featuring Julia Michaels}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = If the World Was Ending\n| cover         = If the World Was Ending by Saxe and Michaels.png\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[JP Saxe]] featuring [[Julia Michaels]]\n| EP            = Hold It Together\n| released      = {{Start date|2019|10|19|mf=yes}}\n| format        =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded      = July 2019\n| genre         = \n| length        = {{Duration|m=3|s=28}}\n| label         = [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n| writer        = {{hlist|[[JP Saxe|Jonathan Percy Starker Saxe]]|[[Julia Michaels]]<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/119496335/credits|title=Credits / If the World Was Ending (feat. Julia Michaels) / Jp Saxe|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| producer      = [[Finneas O'Connell|FINNEAS]]<ref name=\"Tidal\"/>\n| chronology    = [[JP Saxe]]\n| prev_title    = Women Who Look Like You\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| next_title    = Sad Corny F**k\n| next_year     = 2020\n| misc          = {{Extra chronology\n| artist        = [[Julia Michaels]]\n| type          = single \n| prev_title    = [[If You Need Me (Julia Michaels song)|If You Need Me]]\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| title         = If the World Was Ending\n| year          = 2019\n| next_title    = [[Cool Anymore]]\n| next_year     = 2019\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|1jO2wSpAoxA|title=\"If the World Was Ending\"}}|type=single}}\n}}\n\n\"'''If the World Was Ending'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[JP Saxe]], featuring vocals of American singer [[Julia Michaels]]. The song was released by [[Arista Records]] on October 19, 2019, through digital download and streaming formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/if-the-world-was-ending-feat-julia-michaels-single/1482468336|title=If the World Was Ending \u2013 Single|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking to [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']], Michaels said \"I discovered JP's music and posted about him around the same time he was listening to ''[[Inner Monologue Part 1|Inner Monologue]]''. Since we were fans of each other's music, we got together for a writing session.\" Saxe added \"Writing this song with Julia was one of the most creative experiences of my life. We wrote it the day we met and recorded it that same day.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8533210/jp-saxe-julia-michaels-if-the-world-was-ending-video |title=JP Saxe & Julia Michaels Prepare For the Apocalypse in 'If The World Was Ending' Video: Watch |website=Billboard|date= October 17, 2019|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMichaels said \"The song is about that person in your life who you would come back to if the world was ending, when nothing else matters and there is nothing left to hold you back.\"<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n'''Digital download'''\n# \"If the World Was Ending\" \u2013 3:28\n\n'''Remixes'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/au/album/if-the-world-was-ending-feat-julia-michaels-remixes-single/1499729618|title=If the World Was Ending (Remixes) \u2013 Single by JP Saxe on Apple Music|website=Apple Music|date=January 31, 2020|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n# \"If the World Was Ending\" ([[Marian Hill]] remix) \u2013 3:27\n# \"If the World Was Ending\" (Other remix) \u2013 2:29\n# \"If the World Was Ending\" (Original) \u2013 3:28\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2020/1/aria-chart-watch-560/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #560|publisher=auspOp|date=January 18, 2020|accessdate=